Bring a large #saucepan{} of water to the boil with @salt{1/4%tsp} for the noodles.

In the meantime, peel and grate the @garlic cloves{2}(peeled and grated) (or use a #garlic press{}). Trim the @pak choi{1}(trimmed), then cut widthways into 2cm slices. Trim the @green beans{80%g}(trimmed), then cut into thirds.

When boiling, add the @egg noodle nest{125%g} to the water and cook until tender, ~{4%minutes}.

Once cooked, drain in a #sieve{} and run under cold water to stop them sticking together.

Heat a drizzle of @oil{drizzle} in a large #frying pan{} on medium-high heat.

Once hot, add the @British beef mince{120%g} and green beans. Stir-fry until the mince has browned and the beans are starting to soften, ~{6-7%minutes}. Use a #spoon{} to break the mince up as it cooks.

Once the mince has browned, drain and discard any excess fat. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw mince. It's cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

Add the pak choi and @coleslaw mix{120%g}. Stir-fry until the veg has softened, ~{3-4%minutes}.

Stir in the garlic and @ginger puree{15%g}. Stir-fry until fragrant, ~{1%minute}.

Add the @hoisin sauce{128%g}, @soy sauce{15%ml}, @water{50%ml}(for the sauce), and half the @sriracha sauce{30%g} (add less if you'd prefer things milder) to the beef. Stir to combine.

Bring to the boil and simmer until slightly thickened, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Add the cooked noodles to the pan, tossing them to coat them in the sauce. Add a splash more water if you feel it needs it.

Taste and season with salt and pepper if needed, then remove from the heat.

Share your spicy beef noodles between your #bowls{}.

Drizzle over the remaining sriracha (add less if you prefer things milder) and sprinkle over the @roasted white sesame seeds{5%g} to finish.

Enjoy!